<subsection>
  <title>The Pythagorean Theorem</title>
  <p>
    The Pythagorean Theorem states that if <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are the lengths of
    the sides of a right triangle and <m>c</m> is the length of the hypotenuse,
    then <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m>. 
  </p>
  <theorem xml:id="thm-Pythagorean">
    <title>Pythagorean Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose <m>\Delta ABC</m> is a right triangle with right angle at <m>C</m>.
        Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be the lengths of legs <m>\overline{BC}</m> and 
        <m>\overline{AC}</m>, respectively, and let <m>c</m> be the length of the 
        hypotenuse <m>\overline{AB}</m>. Then <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <p>
    The next set of questions will refresh your skill in 
    using the Pythagorean Theorem to determine missing lengths.
  </p>
  <reading-questions>
    <title>Check your Understanding</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A triangle has legs of length 5 and 7. Determine the length of the 
          hypotenuse.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\sqrt{74}\approx8.602</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>a = 5</m> and <m>b = 7</m>. Thus, <m>\sqrt{5^2 + 7^2} = \sqrt{74} \approx 8.602</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A square has a diagonal of length <m>\sqrt{80}</m>. Determine the 
          length of the sides.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          Since the sides of a square are the same length, use the same letter 
          to represent all of them. How do you create a triangle from a square?
        </p>
      </hint>
      <answer>
        <p>
          <m>\sqrt{40}=2\sqrt{10}\approx 6.325</m>
        </p>
      </answer>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="2.5.2.2-cyu-solution">
          <caption></caption>
          <image source="2.5.2.2CYU.png">
            <shortdescription>A squre with diagonal of length squre root of 80.</shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          We are given <m>c = \sqrt{80}</m>. The diagonal cuts the square into two right triangles
          <m>\triangle ABC</m> and <m>\triangle DCB</m>. Therefore, let 
          <m>a = \overline{AB} = \overline{AC} = \overline{CD} = \overline{BD}</m>. Apply the theorem: 
          <m>\sqrt{2a^2} = \sqrt{80} \rightarrow 2a^2 = 80 \rightarrow a^2 = 40 \rightarrow 
            a = \sqrt{40} = 2\sqrt{10} \approx 6.325
          </m> 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </reading-questions>
</subsection>
<subsection>
  <title>Proving the Pythagorean Theorem with Picture Puzzles</title>
  <p>
    The Pythagorean Theorem is very useful, but it is also somewhat mysterious.
    Why does the formula work for all right triangles? Surprisingly, there are 
    more than 350 recognized proofs of the Pythagorean Theorem. We will look at 
    just a few. In the following exploration,
    you will rearrange polygons built from a right triangle,
    and use the rearrangements to explain why 
    <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m> in each case. You are encouraged to try all the proofs in 
    this section and to choose one to learn well enough to convince others.
  </p>
  <aside>
    <p>
      The book, <em>The Pythagorean Proposition</em>, by Elisha S. Loomis, (NCTM:1968) 
      contains 367 proofs of the Pythagorean Theorem. 
      <!--also he published a nonproof in 1901.--> 
    </p>
  </aside>
  
