                  <p>
                    Demonstrate by an example that it is not always possible to create 
                    a Pythagorean triple from two given integers. In other words, name two 
                    integers, <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, such that <m>a^2+b^2</m> is not equal
                    to a perfect square.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Choose two positive integers. Call the smaller one <m>j</m> and 
                    the larger one <m>k</m>.
                    <ol>
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Compute <m>2jk</m> and call it <m>a</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Compute <m>k-j</m> and call it <m>b</m>.
                        </p>
                      </li> 
                      <li>
                        <p>
                          Is there a third positive integer <m>c</m> such that
                          <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> form a Pythagorean triple?
                          If so, what is <m>c</m>?
                        </p>
                      </li>
                    </ol>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use algebra to demonstrate that the sum of <m>(2jk)^2</m> and 
                    <m>(k-j)^2</m> is always a perfect square when <m>j</m> and <m>k</m>
                    are positive integers with <m>j\lt k</m>. What does this tell you 
                    about Pythagorean triples?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
